Normal or Canonical Forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes we need to prove the equivalences of two compound propositions
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, and it seems difficult.
 Then we use an alternative strategy.
 We convert 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}\equiv q^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Elementary
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Product A combination of propositional variables and their negations using
 disjunctions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Elementary
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Sum A combination of propositional variables and their negations using conjuncti
ons
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An elementary sum is identically 
\series bold
True
\series default
 or tautology if it contains at least one pair of factors in which one is
 the negation of other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An elementary sum is identically 
\series bold
False
\series default
 or contradiction if it contains at least one pair of factors in which one
 is the negation of other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Disjunctive Normal Form (DNF)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is the combination of elementary products using conjunction only.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Conjunctive Normal Form (CNF)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is the combination of elementary sums using disjunction only.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Principal DNF
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a given formula, an equivalent formula with sums or disjunctions of
 the minterms (elementary products with each variable occuring exactly once)
 is called the principal CNF.
 It is also called the sum of products form.
 For example, for three propositional variables 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 the possible minterms are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $p\wedge q\wedge r$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $p\wedge q\wedge\neg r$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $p\wedge\neg q\wedge r$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $p\wedge\neg q\wedge\neg r$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\neg p\wedge q\wedge r$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\neg p\wedge q\wedge\neg r$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\neg p\wedge\neg q\wedge r$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\neg p\wedge\neg q\wedge\neg r$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Principal CNF
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a given formula, an equivalent formula with products or conjunctions
 of the maxterms (elementary sums with each variable occurring exactly once)
 is called the principal DNF.
 It is also called the product of sums form.
 The maxterms are the same as the minterms in representation except for
 the fact that disjunctions are used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No two minterms are equivalent.
 The same holds for maxterms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the formula is a tautology, then all the minterms are present in the
 principal DNF form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a contradiction, principal CNF form has all the maxterms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note that maxterms are duals of minterms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Conversion of Expression to Principal DNF without Truth Tables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Replace 
\begin_inset Formula $p\rightarrow q$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg p\vee q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\leftrightarrow q$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $(\neg p\vee q)\wedge(\neg q\vee p)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use De Morgan Laws and Distributivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Drop any elementary product which is a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Introduce the missing factors if necessary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Repeated terms, if any are replaced with a single instance of that term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, let us consider 
\begin_inset Formula $p\rightarrow q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{flalign*}
p\rightarrow q & \equiv\neg p\vee q\\
 & \equiv(\neg p\wedge\mbox{T})\vee(q\wedge\mbox{T}) & \mbox{Identity Law}\\
 & \equiv(\neg p\wedge(q\vee\neg q))\vee(q\wedge(p\vee\neg p)) & \mbox{Negation Law}\\
 & \equiv(\neg p\wedge q)\vee(\neg p\wedge\neg q)\vee(q\wedge p)\vee(q\wedge\neg p) & \mbox{Distributivity}\\
 & \equiv(\neg p\wedge q)\vee(\neg p\wedge\neg q)\vee(p\wedge q)\vee(\neg p\wedge q) & \mbox{Commutativity}\\
 & \equiv(\neg p\wedge q)\vee(\neg p\wedge\neg q)\vee(p\wedge q) & \mbox{Idempotent Law}
\end{flalign*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
Obtain the principal DNF of 
\begin_inset Formula $(p\wedge q)\vee(\neg p\wedge r)\vee(q\wedge r)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Conversion of Expression from Principal DNF to Principal CNF
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the principal DNF of a formula is given, then the principal CNF can be
 found out by finding the disjunction of minterms which do not appear in
 the DNF, and converting it to its dual.
 For example, for 
\begin_inset Formula $p\rightarrow q$
\end_inset

, the principal DNF doesnt have 
\begin_inset Formula $p\wedge\neg q$
\end_inset

 (only one term), so its principal CNF is just 
\begin_inset Formula $p\vee\neg q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

