\begin_layout Section
Methods of Proof
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Proof A proof is a valid argument that establishes the truth of any mathematical
 statement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Theorem A theorem is the universal quantification of a mathematical statement
 (generally conditionals) with one or more premises and a conclusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Proposition Less important theorems are called propositions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Axiom Assumed statements are called axioms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Lemma A lemma is a less important theorem helpful in the proof of other
 theorems or results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Corollary A corollary is the result or a theorem directly established from
 another proved theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Techniques of Proof
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally proofs are done directly or indirectly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Direct In direct proofs, hypotheses are assumed 
\series bold
True
\series default
 and with axioms, definitions and rules of inferences etc.
 we try to prove that the conclusion is also 
\series bold
True
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Indirect We try and prove the contrapositive of the conclusion, or use contradic
tion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with the negation of the conclusion or a negation of the hypotheses
 and reach a logical contradiction.
 If the premises are 
\begin_inset Formula $p=p_{1}\wedge\dotsb\wedge p_{n}$
\end_inset

 then we try to prove in contradiction method, that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\wedge\neg q$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
True
\series default
 (and reach a contradiction).
 This is because
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\wedge\neg q\equiv\neg(\neg p\vee q)\equiv\neg(p\rightarrow q)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Give a direct proof of the statement 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is an even integer, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 is also an even integer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists k,n=2k$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}=(2k)^{2}=4k^{2}\equiv0\mod2$
\end_inset

.
 Hence for even 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 is also even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 is an odd integer, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is also odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us solve this by contradiction.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 is odd
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is odd
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Then we start with 
\begin_inset Formula $p\wedge\neg q$
\end_inset

.
 So, let us assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 is odd and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even, we can assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists k,n=2k$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}=4k^{2}\equiv0\mod2$
\end_inset

.
 But because 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 is odd, so it should be that 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}\equiv1\mod2$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we reached a contradiction.
 Hence the opposite must be 
\series bold
True
\series default
, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 were odd, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 must be odd
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Using contradiction, prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 is irrational.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us assume that on the contrary, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 is rational.
 Then by the definition of rational numbers, for 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 co-primes 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $q\neq0$
\end_inset

) we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{2}=\frac{p}{q}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Squaring, we get 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}=2q^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}\equiv0\mod2$
\end_inset

.
 So, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 must be even (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists k,p=2k$
\end_inset

).
 Using this fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $4k^{2}=2q^{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $2k^{2}=q^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 That says that 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}$
\end_inset

 is even, which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is even.
 But if 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is even and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is even, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 have a common factor 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, so they are no longer co-prime.
 Hence we face a contradiction.
 So, the opposite must be 
\series bold
True
\series default
, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 must be irrational
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Prove by contradiction that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $3n+2$
\end_inset

 is odd, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is odd
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 be even.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists k,n=2k$
\end_inset

.
 That states 
\begin_inset Formula $3n+2=6k+2=2(3k+1)\equiv0\mod2$
\end_inset

.
