\begin_inset Formula $P(k+1)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
True
\series default
 using the hypotheses.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Example
Show by mathematical induction that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{1\cdot2}+\frac{1}{2\cdot3}+\dotsb+\frac{1}{n(n+1)}=\frac{n}{n+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Basis Step
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $P(1)$
\end_inset

 is true because
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{1\cdot2}=\frac{1}{1+1}=\frac{1}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\series bold
Hypothesis Step
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Let us assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
True 
\series default
for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n=k$
\end_inset

.
 So the following statement holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{1\cdot2}+\frac{1}{2\cdot3}+\dotsb+\frac{1}{k(k+1)}=\frac{k}{k+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\series bold
Inductive Step
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Let us try to prove 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k+1)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
True
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(k+1):\,\,\,\frac{k+1}{k+2} & = & \frac{1}{1\cdot2}+\frac{1}{2\cdot3}+\dotsb+\frac{1}{k(k+1)}+\frac{1}{(k+1)(k+2)}\\
 & = & \frac{k}{k+1}+\frac{1}{(k+1)(k+2)}\\
 & = & \frac{k(k+2)}{(k+1)(k+2)}+\frac{1}{(k+1)(k+2)}\\
 & = & \frac{k^{2}+2k+1}{(k+1)(k+2)}\\
 & = & \frac{(k+1)^{2}}{(k+1)(k+2)}\\
 & = & \frac{k+1}{k+2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k+1)$
\end_inset

 holds.
 So, by the law of mathematical induction, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(n)$
\end_inset

 holds for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

