\begin_layout Section
Recursively Defined Sequences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are sequences which are defined in terms of themselves.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=3^{n},n\in\mathbf{W}$
\end_inset

 can be described as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a_{0} & = & 1\\
a_{n+1} & = & 3a_{n}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proces of getting the elements using the previous elements in this fashion
 is called recursion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Program Correctness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A program is said to be correct if it produces the correct output for every
 possible input.
 A correctness proof typically consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 steps -
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Show that if the program terminates, then a correct answer is obtained.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Show that the program does terminate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we can prove the first step only, then the program is said to be 
\series bold
partially correct
\series default
.
 Let there be a program with input 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and output 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 Then, a program or program segment 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is said to be partially correct with respect to the inital assertion 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and final assertion 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is true for all the inputs of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and on termination, 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is true for all the outputs of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 We usually then write it as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p & \{S\} & q
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
This is called a 
\series bold
Hoare Triple
\series default
.
 In general,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p & \{S_{1}\} & q\\
p & \{S_{2}\} & q
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 can be written as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p & \{S_{1},S_{2}\} & q
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

